				</bibl>

				<!-- D/JQA/24.1665 -->

				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-01">
					<head>1 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-01"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<dateline>
							<hi rend="italic">April 1799.</hi>
						</dateline>
						<p><date>1. </date>In the Evening at the German play; saw a Comedy of
								<persRef ref="kotzbue-august">Kotzebue</persRef>— Das kind der
							Liebe. Upon my return home, found <persRef ref="brown-mary">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> and her <persRef
								ref="brown-margaret;brown-isabella;brown-fanny">daughters</persRef>,
								<persRef ref="talbot-charles">Lord Talbot</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef>
							and <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Richards</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-02">
					<head>2 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-02"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>2. </date>Called this forenoon at <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Schickler’s</persRef>— Evening at a Ball at <persRef
								ref="arnim-friedrich">Count Arnim’s</persRef>.— The <persRef
								ref="louiseauguste">Queen</persRef> came from Potsdam to attend it—
							The <persRef ref="frederick-william-iii">king</persRef> did not come.
							They went there the 30<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> of last month— Played
							Whist, with <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">lle:</hi> de
								Hagen</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">M. de Sydow</persRef>, and the
							<persRef ref="u">Chamberlain de Buck</persRef>. <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
									rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>. at <persRef ref="brown-charles"
									>D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-03">
					<head>3 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-03"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>3. </date>Dined at <persRef ref="schulenburgkehnert-frederick"
								>Count Schulenburg’s</persRef> with a large company of Ladies and
							Gentlemen. <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> A.</persRef> did not go. Had much conversation at
							table with <persRef ref="u">Countess Piper</persRef> a Swedish Lady.—
							Called in the afternoon upon <persRef ref="livingston-edward2">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Livingston</persRef>, who is ill with the
							gout.— <persRef ref="talbot-charles">Lord Talbot</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="vankinckel-hendrik">Admiral Kinckel</persRef>, &amp; <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Richards</persRef> were there—
								<persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
								Arbuthnot</persRef> came in— Evening at home.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-04">
					<head>4 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-04"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>4. </date><persRef ref="grenville-thomas">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Grenville</persRef> and his family, <persRef ref="brown-charles"
									>D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown</persRef> &amp; <persRef
								ref="brown-mary;brown-william5">his family</persRef>, except the
								<persRef ref="brown-margaret;brown-isabella;brown-fanny">young
								ladies</persRef>, <persRef ref="talbot-charles">Lord
								Talbot</persRef>, <persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef> &amp; <persRef ref="u">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Sloper</persRef>, dined with us, and some of
							them spent the Evening here— Played chess with D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							Brown— <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A</persRef>. was unwell, the greatest part of the day, with an
							headache—</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-05">
					<head>5 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-05"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>5. </date>Weather continues very cold and the wind easterly.
							Walking under the Linden, met <persRef ref="grenville-thomas">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Grenville</persRef>, and <persRef
								ref="panin-nikita">Count Panin</persRef>.— Evening at the <persRef
								ref="vonheinitz-friedrich">Minister Heinitz’s</persRef> weekly
							assembly, which now recommences after having been for some time
							suspended— Saw there the Swedish <persRef ref="vonfersen-axel">Count
								Fersen</persRef>.— Played Whist with a <persRef ref="u">Countess
								Unruh</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">lle:</hi> de
								Hagen</persRef>, and <persRef ref="u">Col<hi rend="superscript">l:</hi> de
								Hardenberg</persRef>, a brother of the <persRef
								ref="vonhardenberg-karl">Minister</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-06">
					<head>6 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-06"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>6. </date>So busily engaged in the morning, as to neglect in some
							measure my necessary exercise— Evening at the supper party at <persRef
								ref="u">Princess de Sacken’s</persRef>— Did not stay— Supped at
								<persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Brown’s</persRef>, where were <persRef ref="u">Count S<hi rend="superscript"
									>t:</hi> George</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Curtoys</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-07">
					<head>7 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-07"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>7. </date>Unwell, the former part of the day.— Snowed almost all
							the morning, but afterwards turned to rain. Evening at a private play at
								<persRef ref="cohen-ephraim">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Cohen’s</persRef>— Le Barbier de Seville and le Somnambule.— The
							first was tolerably well performed.— The Hall, excessively crowded with
							company.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-08">
					<head>8 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-08"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>8. </date>Am better— Dined at <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Schickler’s</persRef>, with a large company of Ladies
							and Gentlemen— Met there a Spaniard whom I had seen at Petersbourg
							sixteen years ago, and a brother of <persRef ref="u">Madame
								Sonanéz</persRef> whom I had seen two years ago at the Hague.— Sat
							next the Duke of <persRef ref="alfieri-carlo">Castel Alfieri</persRef> at table, who
							told me much about the <persRef ref="thugut-johann">Baron de Thugut</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="charlesarchdukeofaustria">Archduke Charles</persRef>, and the
							Court of Vienna, where he lately was Sardinian Minister.— Called on
								<persRef ref="livingston-edward2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Livingston</persRef>— Evening at <persRef ref="brown-charles">D<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Brown’s</persRef>—played Chess with him.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-09">
					<head>9 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-09"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="254" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>9. </date>Had a very bad night; more from concern for <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">my wife</persRef> who is unwell, than
							from any illness of my own. Lesson of German this morning.— Evening at
								<persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>.
							Reversi with <persRef ref="vonbruhl-sophia">Countess Brühl</persRef>,
								<persRef ref="u">Countess La Roche Aymon</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="hatzfeldt-franz">General Hatzfeld</persRef>— Afterwards at
								<persRef ref="brown-charles">Doctor Brown’s</persRef>— <persRef
								ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Sanford</persRef>, an English
							Gentleman, with <persRef ref="u">his Lady</persRef> and <hi
								rend="strikethrough">daughters</hi> two Sisters were there— <persRef
								ref="talbot-charles">Lord Talbot</persRef> &amp; <persRef ref="u"
								>Count S<hi rend="superscript">t:</hi> George</persRef>, who go to-morrow
							for Dresden.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-10">
					<head>10 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-10"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>10. </date>Wrote this forenoon to <persRef ref="forbes-john"
								>Forbes</persRef>.— Evening at the supper party at <persRef
								ref="vonheinitz-friedrich">Baron Heinitz’s</persRef>.— Played Casino
							with the <persRef ref="u">Countesses Solms</persRef> and <persRef
								ref="vonarnim-friedrich">Arnim</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">Count
								Nogarola</persRef>, the Gentleman sent to compliment the <persRef
								ref="frederick-william-iii">king</persRef> by the new <persRef
								ref="maximilian-i">Elector of Bavaria</persRef>, upon his
							accession.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-11">
					<head>11 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-11"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>11. </date>Lesson of German this morning.— <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>.
							went with <persRef ref="u;u">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> and the Miss
								Sanford’s</persRef>, English Ladies now here, to visit the Ladies of
							the <persRef ref="louiseauguste">Queen</persRef> and Princesses.— Began
							again, where I had left <persRef ref="riqueti-honore"
								>Mirabeau’s</persRef> book upon the Prussian Monarchy— Evening an
							hour or two at the Casino.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-12">
					<head>12 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-12"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>12. </date>Writing to the <persRef ref="pickering-timothy">Sec<hi
									rend="superscript">y:</hi> of State</persRef>— Evening at <persRef
								ref="panin-nikita">Count Panin’s</persRef>, where we saw performed a
							couple of french plays. La Gageure imprévue, and Le sourd. With a sort
							of Prologue and Epilogue informing that the occasion was the recovery of
							the <persRef ref="panin-sophia">Countess</persRef> from her illness.—
							The plays were well performed.— <persRef ref="deriquet-victor">Count
								Caraman</persRef> acted with great applause.— Several others
							likewise gave much pleasure—</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-13">
					<head>13 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-13"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>13. </date>We breakfasted with the <persRef ref="frederica-louise2"
								>Queen mother</persRef> in a hot-house, belonging to a Garden just
							out of town— The company was curiously selected— Among the rest was
								<persRef ref="lucchesini-carlotta">Madame de Lucchesini</persRef>,
							and her friend <persRef ref="u">Madame de Halberg</persRef>, a woman separated from her husband,
							and who has come from Vienna here in pursuit of <persRef ref="u">Graves</persRef> her lover. The
							queen told her this morning that she had invited Graves on purpose that
							she might meet him; She was glad to see them so well together, and hoped
							it would last.— Evening at a party and supper at <persRef
								ref="schulenburgkehnert-frederick">Count Schulenburg’s</persRef>—
							Whist with <persRef ref="u;u">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> and Miss
								Sanford</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Martin</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-14">
					<head>14 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-14"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>14. </date>Dined at <persRef ref="vonmollendorf-richard">Marshall
								Moellendorf’s</persRef> with a company of thirty persons.— Walk with
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> before dinner Called in the afternoon to see
								<persRef ref="livingston-edward2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Livingston</persRef> who is much better of his Gout— M<hi rend="superscript"
								>rs:</hi> A— went to the play. Received several Letters from
								<persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
							King</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-15">
					<head>15 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-15"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>15. </date>Answered <persRef ref="king-rufus">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> King’s</persRef> Letters— Had little time to walk—
							Evening at the Play— Saw a Comedy of <persRef ref="iffland-august"
								>Iffland</persRef> called Old Times and new Times— His old moral, of
							dissuading the citizens from affecting the style of living and expence
							of the novelty— There is a sort of contrast between his Dramatic
							character and that of <persRef ref="kotzbue-august">Kotzebue</persRef>—
							Iffland’s morals are much the best.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-16">
					<head>16 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-16"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>16. </date>Read <persRef ref="carnot-lazare">Carnot’s</persRef>
							defence of himself against <persRef ref="bailleul-jacques"
								>Bailleul</persRef>, which <persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef> sent me.— Evening at
								<persRef ref="vonzinzendorf-friedrich">Count Zinzendorf’s</persRef>
							Ball and Supper, which he gives upon taking leave— He goes to Dresden to
							be Minister at War.— I did not go early enough to see the Ladies crown
							him with flowers, and sing the couplets to his honour.— Came away
							immediately after supper.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-17">
					<head>17 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-17"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>17. </date>Received this morning a Letter from my brother <persRef
								ref="adams-thomas">Thomas</persRef> at Philadelphia— The first I
							have from him since he sailed.— Partly answered it— Evening at <persRef
								ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>.— Played
							Reversi with <persRef ref="u">Madame de Nogarola</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">Miss
								Bischoffwerder</persRef> and <persRef ref="bunau-gunther">Count
								Bünau</persRef>— Stayed to Supper.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-18">
					<head>18 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-18"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>18. </date>Finished my letter to <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my
								brother</persRef>— But had little time for exercise— Evening at the
								<persRef ref="wilhelminaofhesse">Princess Henry’s</persRef>.— Played
							Casino with <persRef ref="u">Miss Otterstaett</persRef>, and the
								<persRef ref="u;vonschrotter-friedrich">Ministers Werder and
								Schroetter</persRef>— Stayed to supper— The Princess having obtained
							leave from the <persRef ref="frederick-william-iii">king</persRef>, to
							depart from the old established rule and invite the foreign Ministers to
							supper.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-19">
					<head>19 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-19"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>19. </date>Dined at the Casino— A Pic-nic dinner given to <persRef
								ref="vonzinzendorf-friedrich">Count Zinzendorf</persRef> upon his
							departure— There were about forty persons present— Evening at home—
								<persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Sanford</persRef>, <persRef
								ref="u">his Lady</persRef> and Sisters passed the Evening with
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">us</persRef>, as did <persRef
								ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef>.
							received various letters and Packets from America.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-20">
					<head>20 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-20"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<pb n="255" type="ms"/>
						<p><date>20. </date>Lesson of German in the morning. Letters to <persRef
								ref="murray-william2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="pitcairn-joseph">Pitcairn</persRef>— Evening at the
								<persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">Minister Alvensleben’s</persRef>,
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								A.</persRef> did not go— Played Casino with the young Countess Arnim
								<persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Warburg</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="neale-ferdinand">Count Neale</persRef>.— A time of
							great anxiety now begins with much to fear, and little to hope.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-21">
					<head>21 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-21"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>21. </date><persRef ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Garlike</persRef> called on me this forenoon— Walk with <persRef
								ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>.
							under the Linden— Afternoon at the Casino. Evening, a couple of hours at
								<persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sanford’s</persRef> lodgings
							at the Hotel de Russie.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-22">
					<head>22 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-22"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>22. </date>Busily writing all the forenoon— Weather rainy the
							greatest part of the day, could therefore walk but little.— Read this
							Evening the first Act of <persRef ref="shakespeare-william"
								>Shakespeare’s</persRef>
							<persRef ref="richardthe3rd">Richard the 3<hi rend="superscript"
								>d:</hi></persRef></p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-23">
					<head>23 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-23"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>23. </date>Lesson of German; writing all the forenoon.— <persRef
								ref="brown-mary">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Brown</persRef> and
								<persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> Sanford</persRef>, to
							spend the Evening. <persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>r:</hi> Arbuthnot</persRef> likewise passed an hour with us—
								<persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef> taken ill.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-24">
					<head>24 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-24"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>24. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> confined all day to her bed— Such
							times, must be to me times of idleness. Did nothing but read the
							American newspapers— Evening first at <persRef ref="u">Countess
								Eichstett</persRef>, and afterwards at <persRef
								ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>.— Whist, with
							the <persRef ref="u">Minister Buchholz</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">M<hi
								rend="superscript">r:</hi> Sydow</persRef>, and <persRef ref="yorck-hans">Major Wartenberg</persRef></p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-25">
					<head>25 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-25"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>25. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> extremely ill all night, and not much
							relieved even through this whole day.— Was with her almost all day— Read
							a little, but could not write.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-26">
					<head>26 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-26"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>26. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
									>rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> beginning to get better— Found myself
							able to write a very little; but passed the greatest part of the day
							with her— English Papers— Paragraph of American news— Read the
							Anti-Jacobin Review.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-27">
					<head>27 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-27"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>27. </date>Lesson of German again this morning.— Walk in the Park.—
								<persRef ref="brown-isabella">Miss B. Brown</persRef> in the
							afternoon— Evening at home— Reading the Appendix to <persRef
								ref="riqueti-honore">Mirabeau’s</persRef> book upon the Prussian
							Monarchy.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-28">
					<head>28 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-28"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>28. </date>My old friend <persRef ref="forbes-john">J.
								Forbes</persRef> called on me this morning, and dined with me. He
							comes last from Stettin and is going back to Hamburg, and thence to
							England— Evening at the <persRef ref="catherine">Duchess of
								Holstein-Beck’s</persRef>, at the performance of a couple of short
							french plays— La bonne Mere; and Les battus ne payent pas toujours
							l’amende.— Afterwards played whist, with <persRef ref="u">Madame de
								Saldern</persRef>, the <persRef ref="u">Minister Buchholz</persRef>,
							and <persRef ref="lehndorff-ernst">Count Lehndorf</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-29">
					<head>29 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-29"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Health and Illness</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>29. </date><persRef ref="arbuthnot-robert">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Arbuthnot</persRef> and <persRef ref="brown-william5">William
								Brown</persRef> called this morning— In the afternoon I went to see
								<persRef ref="livingston-edward2">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi>
								Livingston</persRef>, who is yet ill of the gout. Evening at home
							with <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
								Adams</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-30">
					<head>30 April 1799</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04-30"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
						<subject>Recreation</subject>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p><date>30. </date>Lesson of German— <persRef ref="forbes-john"
								>Forbes</persRef> called on me. He goes for Hamburg this morning.
							Writing to <persRef ref="adams-thomas">my brother</persRef>. Evening at
							Bellevue— Whist with <persRef ref="u">Madame de Krusemark</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">M<hi
									rend="superscript">lle:</hi> Hagen</persRef> &amp; <persRef ref="u">M<hi
									rend="superscript">r:</hi> Helbig</persRef>.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1799-04-xx">
					<head>Day</head>
					<bibl>
						<author>JQA</author>
						<date type="creation" when="1799-04"/>
						<editor role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					</bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
						<p>
							<date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>—</date> As the last Month.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
